description.text:
This is my total redesign of the pet waste bag dispenser. This fixes all the things I wasn't totally happy with in my first version: ease of printing, grip on the bags, tearing consistency.

I know it looks odd and different than all other dispensers but it is much better for starting a new roll, gripping the next bag and tearing off a bag.

There are two versions. One for bags with holes in the perforations (like produce bags at the grocery store) and one for bags with perforation all the way across (like the Amazon basics bags).

You will need:
1 holder (dispenser)
2 clips
1 door
1 ring

TIP: For the Amazon basics bags, line up the tip of the arrow with the top of the tear slot and the perforation should be lined up with the cutting edge.

description.text:
The Waichulis Form Box is a learning device that contains several basic geometric solids, or ‘forms’, that can be configured in a variety of ways to compare and contrast the way light describes them.


This project contains two files which are listed in 'Thing Files'.

  • Form Box without Cylinder and Sphere- The form box contains a nested cone, cube, a rectilinear/curvilinear cubical solid and new nested pyramid. A cylinder can be purchased at your local hardware store from a piece of white PVC. A sphere can be purchased separately. This would be the cheapest option.
  • Form Box without Sphere- The form box contains a nested cone, cube, a rectilinear/curvilinear cubical solid, a new nested pyramid and a cylinder. A sphere can be purchased separately.



For those looking to assemble the most economical Form Box possible we recommend printing the Form Box without a Cylinder and Sphere and adding in a standard white Field Hockey ball (which has a 2.8” diameter) for the sphere and a piece of white PVC pipe (3” diameter) cut to about 4” in length.


The Waichulis Form Box is an art tool that was made to be used with the
Language of Drawing and Language of Painting Instructional Core Program.

title: Warhammer Quest (1995) Orc Proxies
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I'm working on a complete set of printed proxies to cover the entire range of possible rolls on all 10 levels of the monster tables from the WHQ Roleplay Book.

I only ever owned the base set, and I always wanted to collect them all but could never afford it when they were still on the market.

I've leaned heavily on dutchmogul's amazing collection of gaming miniatures. Some of these figures are only resized versions of his, some are modded versions of his, and a rare few are scratch modeled by me.

I've gone through the list and pared it down as much as possible. My goal is to handle any given roll, but not worry about trying to cover any two rolls... I chose not to distinguish between a Savage Ork and a Black Ork, for example, and I only considered An Ork to differ from and Ork champion if they could both appear on the same roll. I wasn't too uptight about hand weapons... Swords, Spears, Axes... whatever. So you basically end up with Orks, a Big Ork, and a Bigger Ork. Finally, if you have 2D6 goblins that you roll for bows or spears, I choose to take that as 1D6 w/bow and 1D6 with spears to keep the numbers down, but print as many as you want!

This is the Orcs, up to ~battle level 7, for level 8 you'd just need to figure out a Big Shaman too. More races to follow.

6 Orc Archers (Could also use Dreth Hurler
6 Orc Spearmen
1 Orc Shaman
1 Orc Boss
1 Orc Warboss

I deeply appreciate tips if you like my work, but in this case please consider sending some love dutchmogul's way, as his amazing work made this possible!

description.text: This is a camera mount for a GoPro camera designed to fit into the top of your walking stick (after you drill a hole that is the right size). I made it for the person who runs www.justtrails.com as he uses the GoPro to take lots of pictures for the hiking enthusiasts that use his web site. There are 2 styles in this thing. The bigger one requires a very long M4 bolt which goes thru the shaft and into the body of the camera mount making it very sturdy and not likely to break unless you find that you need to fend off a bear or your mother-in-law or something in which case I make no warranty as to the strength of the mount. I will, however, print one for you if you happen to break yours while fending off a bear. I'm jus' sayin' .... The second and smaller of the two is probably sufficient for most people and is pretty strong. I did find the support material very difficult to remove so I decide that it will function as a "key" to keep it from rotating in the hole (rather than admit I have a design flaw). When I ran the STL thru my slic3r, I got the infamous errors that basically tell me I'm not an engineer (go figure) so I ran the STL thru netfabb (http://cloud.netfabb.com/) and had them fix it for me. The files that have been fixed have the word "fixed" in the file name.

for the larger of the two, print it. Grab an M4 about 40mm long and a pair of channel lock pliers.
Hold the round shaft with the pliers and squeeze very hard. Then crank the M4 thru the shaft till it protrudes a couple MM. Insert the shaft in the main body and finish cranking on the M4 till it's all snug. Attach your GoPro to the holder.
Drill a hole in the top of your walking stick such that either of the 2 shafts will fit and you have a built in stead-i-cam mount to take pics of your favorite hiking trail (or your buddy fending off a bear with his hiking stick).
Of course, you are free to use it any way you want...
the smaller mount probably needs no explanation, other than you may need to file/sand the support material off or you can use it as a 'key' to keep it from rotating in the hole
oh, one other thing ... I also posted my slic3r.rc file in case it helps

Each time I'm maintain or repair something at my RF100, the y-axis crashed the front or the x-axis crashed the end-stop. So I decided to create a prevention. Just clip these spacers over the rails, so you can rotate your printer in any position without damage. The axes are fixed now.
It's doesnt matter how brilliant the prints comes out, the function is the important spot.
You'll need x-axis right/left and TWO y-stopper. It's possible to print the y-stopper at the RF100 if you turn the print position to 45 degrees (Corner to corner; even skirt is possible). You'll have a bit of space between the stoppers for simple mount and dismantle.

Jedes Mal wenn ich etwas an meinen RF100 repariere, crasht die y-achse gegen die Front oder die x-achse crasht den Endschalter. Also habe ich eine Vorkehrung erstellt. Die Abstandshalter werden einfach über die Schienen geclipst, dadurch kann der Drucker in jede Position gedreht werden, ohne das etwas kaputt gehen kann. Die Achsen sind nun fixiert. Es ist nicht von wichtig wie die Drucke aussehen, die Funktion ist wichtig.
Es werden X-Axis right/left und ZWEI mal Y-Stopper benötigt. Es ist möglich auf dem RF100 die Y-Stopper zudrucken. Hierfür muss der Druck um 45 Grad gedreht werden (Ecke zu Ecke; ein Skirt ist dann ebenfalls möglich). Zwischen den Stoppern ist etwas Spiel um eine einfache Montage und Demontage zu ermöglichen.

Cuphead and Mugman are here! Whether you rage quit the game, or love the punishment, one thing is for sure, Cuphead is a beatiful game. So I was very excited to try to bring these two to life.

description.text:
Decilo! es un dispositivo pensado para ser usado como herramienta comunicacional, ya sea en terapias de estimulación del habla ó como dispositivo intercomunicador para personas con dificultad para comunicarse. Pueden verlo andando aquí: https://www.facebook.com/hipatetik/videos/10213369402802882/

El dispositivo opera a partir de un módulo dfplayer en módo autónomo
(ver sección AD KEY MODE en https://www.dfrobot.com/wiki/index.php/DFPlayer_Mini_SKU:DFR0299)

Se adjunta el PCB para ser realizado en formato gcode con una impresora, utilizando el método propuesto en www.lamja.com/?p=635 (entre mis objetos publicados hay un soporte para grabar los pcbs si tienes una Flyingbear P902). También adjunto el archivo en Fritzing.

El ensamblado es relativamente sencillo, y como partes adicionales se requiere:

Módulo DFplayer Mini
PCB simple faz 5x5cm
Resistencias y capacitores varios (ver archivo Fritzing y esquemático)
Tornillos M3 de 1,5cm de largo x 6
Tornillos autoperforantes pequeños x 5
Pulsadores soft touch 12mm x8
Cable multipar 4 hilos (recomendado) 30cm
Parlante 40-60mm de diámetro.
Switch inversor interruptor tamaño mediano.
Opcional: Jacks 3,5mm para salidas auxiliares.
Portapilas AA para 4 pilas.
Pegamento La Gotita o similar.

Soldador, destornilladores, cutter, etc.

Si te gustó este diseño, y querés ayudarme para que siga investigando y desarrollando, podés dejarme un "tip" (ver botón correspondiente)

Decilo! (Say it!) is a device designed to be used as a communication tool, either in speech stimulation therapies or as an intercom device for people with difficulty communicating. You can see it walking here: https://www.facebook.com/hipatetik/videos/10213369402802882/

The device operates from a dfplayer module in autonomous mode
 (see section AD KEY MODE at https://www.dfrobot.com/wiki/index.php/DFPlayer_Mini_SKU:DFR0299)

 The PCB is attached to be made in gcode format with a printer, using the method proposed in www.lamja.com/?p=635 (among my published objects there is a support to record the pcbs if you have a Flyingbear P902). I also attach the file in Fritzing format.

The assembly is relatively simple, and as additional parts are required:

DFplayer Mini module
PCB simple face 5x5cm
Resistances and few capacitors (see Fritzing and schematic file in the link below)
M3 screws 1.5cm long x 6
Small self-drilling screws x 5
Soft touch push buttons 12mm
Inverter switch key
Optional: 3.5mm jacks for auxiliar outputs.
4-wire multipair cable (recommended) 30cm
Speaker 40-60mm in diameter.
AA battery holder for 4 batteries.
Glue The Droplet or similar.

Soldering gun, screwdrivers, cutter, etc.

If you like this design and want to help me to research and develop more gadgets, you can give me a tip.

description.text:
Yet another case for the Raspberry Pi v2 camera. Snap shut back, several mounts. MK2 mount clips on the 10mm Y-axis threaded rods. The MK3 mount is designed to mount to 3030 extrusions such as used in the upcoming Prusa i3 MK3.

The case includes a thumb wheel that takes a 3mm nut and a stand alone base that can be attached to any slat surface. An M3-30mm screw attaches the case to any of the bases. There is also an optional clip that would hold the case together if the internal clips should break.

The two mounts have bases included that slip onto a pin and can rotate. A hole is provided to use a screw to lock the case down, but it seems to be a tight enough fit that I have not needed to use it. The MK2 mount includes integrated cable clips and the MK3 uses separate clips that are modified versions of the Prusa supplied clips for the LED cables. Supports are needed for the MK3 mount. Use the slicer mirror option if you wish to mount in the opposite orientation.

OpenSCAD source files are included for all parts.

author: Boria069

title: Monoprice Maker Select V2 Spool Holder Extender

description.text:
Here's another Monoprice Maker Select V2 spool extender! I couldn't find one that met my needs when I wanted it, but I guess I didn't use the right keywords because now I see a few. Oh well.
This can accommodate a spool up to 93 mm wide, which was perfect for the 1 kg spool of "BuMat" PLA filament I had (92 mm wide). It only works with spools that have a lot of clearance inside, though... see note below.
This one is nice because it just extends the original holder, so it doesn't use as much plastic as an all-new holder, and you don't have to worry about any quality issues with printing screw threads. One small downside is that you'll have to drill a hole through your Monoprice holder.
NOTE! Since this leaves the flange at the end of the existing holder intact, you need a spool with enough room inside to clear this flange. Put one side of your spool on the existing holder and support the other end so that the spool is level... if the spool won't turn freely because that flange is interfering, then this isn't the extender for you! It works perfectly with my ~3 year old BuMat 92mm 1 kg spool, but they may have changed spool designs.

Slide the extender all the way into the end of the Monoprice holder, trimming any brim first if necessary so there's no gap. Use the hole in the extender as a guide to drill a clearance hole for an 8-32 screw. [I had to start the hole with a slightly small drill through my extender, then remove the extender and enlarge the hole in the Monoprice holder with a #18 (11/64") drill.] Use a 1" 8-32 screw, washer, and nut to secure the extender to holder [washer and nut on the extender side.]

Tools required:
  • Needle nose pliers
  • Sharpie marker
    Vitamin BOM
  • Features a 1 watt ultra bright LED (don't stare directly at it, it WILL give you a headache).
    https://www.amazon.com/microtivity-IL706-1-watt-Ultra-bright-White/dp/B0085MOSV2/
  • Powered by 2 watch batteries (377 series, the same I'll be using in upcoming watch project).
    https://www.amazon.com/Energizer-377-376-Watch-Batteries/dp/B01AVJBH8I/
  • 2x 1" of fine gauge copper wire (24 gauge I used)
    Printed BOM
  • Print a ring in your proper size. I uploaded 4 or 5 sizes, and it depends on what finger you want to wear it on. Print a few and see what fits, the sizes are in mm.
  • Print a cap style you like. More cap styles are listed as derivatives.
    Assembly
  • Take your two lengths of copper wire, and bend them in half. From the inside of the ring, insert the ends into the holes such that excess wire is sticking out along the band in both directions. Pull it taught.
  • With the needle nose pliers, pull the wire back through the battery chamber on both sides, so a loop will be sticking up past the batteries.
  • Insert both batteries facing the same direction. They should snap into place, leaving a loop of wire sticking up about 1/2 cm.
  • With pliers, twist the loop 90 degrees, so it will look like little mickey mouse ears along the plane of the ring.
  • Take the microtivity LED, and bend each lead downwards 90 degrees.
  • WITHOUT the LED, insert the cap onto the ring, over the batteries and wires. The wire loops should fit well into the slots, if you look through the hole where the LED will go. When you twist the ring back and forth from on and off, the wire loops should bend along with the cap, but always stay inside their respective grooves. If this is not the case, remove the cap, reform the loops with your pliers, and try again.
  • Once the loops seem to be in the right place, remove the cap.
  • Test the LED against the battery loops. This will ensure your batteries are installed correctly, and will let you know the polarity of the LED. Mark the positive lead with the sharpie.
  • Insert the LED into the cap with your fingers. Wiggle it into place until it slides in flush with the inside of the cap.
  • Align the polarity of the LED with the proper loop, and insert the cap, wiggling as you go until it snaps into the right place.
  • Slowly twist the ring on and off a few times.
    Hopefully then it should work properly! When you're testing, try not to stare into the light too much, it will give you a headache..
    Message if you have any problems!

A friend of mine purchased this metal car at a yard sale. It was missing one wheel but still looked nice. He brought one of the wheels to me to see if I could print a replacement.

I used a profile gauge to copy the profile and then plotted it on graph paper. Next I entered the coordinates into DesignSpark and then did a rotary extrusion. After some minor tweaking, I had a very close replica of the wheel and hubcap.

My friend was thrilled with the results and started cleaning the car up and repainted it. Talk about a blending of old and new technology! We think the car was made in the 1930's.

Second January 2018 update
Breakaway do not seem to work so made a new versions. Pins and locking features are simplified and are now just straight pins no longer built into the assembly. Additionally I made a mistake in the grip connection and made it impossible to connect the two pieces together. This should be resolved, now you need to place upper grip in the slot in the lower grip and then glue the two parts of the lower grip together.
Additionally I uploaded an additional set of files scaled down to 15% and I modified the tolerances accordingly.
Special Thanks to WhiteFang97 for the feedback.

January 2018 update
Modified the Pins and some connection areas. Changed the build now there are 3 parts in the assembly with pins build in. The pins will very easily break away from the main body and will be left lose but enclosed in their housing (you want this). There is 1 pin for each joint. Once each pin is free you can pull them all out to assemble the blade. Then push each of the pins back into place and twist them to lock them in place. This will require a good printer and it will not work it the assembly is scaled down too much as the tolerances will get too small. I have no printed it yet I can not guarantee it will function properly.

-Headless Moose

author: Lanius

description.text:
Part of my "Adventurers Camp" collections. Two different base-style tents with three versions "blinged" up with some adventuring accessories.

  • One tent with a waterskin, bedroll, and pack
  • One tent with a spellbook on a stump, axe, a lute, and a cookpot (from HeroesHorde)
  • One tent with a bedroll, a lantern, a wolf pelt, and a sword/shield.

ABOUT THE ADVENTURERS CAMP: The “Adventurers Camp Collection” (View Collection or See Pics) contains everything you need to create a fleshed-out camp for your adventurers, hunters, bandit party, etc. I personally love small touches, so I tried to use a large mix of accessories and items throughout to make it feel lived-in and fit a fantasy world. There are accessory-free versions of the bedrolls and tents that are easier to paint and can be used in post-apocalyptic or any other genre, and the rest of the items should work well across genres. The design for the bedrolls & tents were heavily influenced by the awesome work of Tiny Furniture and awesome suggestions from folks on Facebook. Stay tuned for more awesome stuff, and feel free to leave a tip if you enjoyed! Also thanks to all the other contributors (aka Dutchmogul, Curufin, etc) who had tons of awesome free items/accessories for me to remix and use!

For printing, I did everything in the pics @ .08mm layer height and a relative slow speed (~35mm/s). Nothing needs supports except the horse tether pole, which needs very little. Make sure you print with 2 or 3 top layers also.

Please check out Ill Gotten Games, Hero's Hoard, and Tiny Furniture if you like this stuff!

If you like my free items on Thingiverse, check out my premium stuff for sale on Hero's Hoard, and follow EC3D on Facebook where I give away premium model sets to a follower twice a month!
